                                                                                 html-5



1>What are the new tags added in HTML5? 
=<article>: Represents a self-contained piece of content that could be distributed and reused independently, such as a news article or blog post.

<aside>: Represents content that is tangentially related to the content around it, such as a sidebar or pull quote.

<details> and <summary>: <details> represents a disclosure widget from which the user can obtain additional information or controls, and <summary> represents a summary or label for the content in a <details> element

<figcaption>: Represents a caption or legend for a <figure> element, typically used with images or diagrams.
<figure>: Represents any content that is referenced from the main content, such as images, charts, or videos
<footer>: Represents a footer section typically containing metadata, copyright information, and links to related documents
<header>: Represents a header section typically containing introductory content, such as headings, logos, and navigation
<main>: Represents the main content of the document, excluding headers, footers, and sidebars
<mark>: Represents text highlighted for reference or notation purposes
<nav>: Represents a navigation menu, typically containing links to other pages or sections of the website.

2> How to embed audio and video in a webpage?
=Embedding Audio:
Use the <audio> element to embed audio files. The controls attribute adds playback controls, allowing users to play, pause, and adjust volume.
controls: Adds playback controls.
<source>: Specifies the audio file source and its type. You can provide multiple <source> elements for different formats to ensure compatibility across browsers
Embedding Video:
Use the <video> element to embed video files. Similar to <audio>, the controls attribute adds playback controls.
controls: Adds playback controls.
width: Specifies the width of the video player.

3> Semantic element in HTML5? 
=<header>:

Represents the header of a section or page.
Typically contains headings, logos, and navigation.

<nav>:

Represents a navigation menu.
Contains links to other pages or sections of the website.

<main>:

Represents the main content of the document.
Excludes headers, footers, and sidebars

<article>:

Represents a self-contained piece of content.
Can be distributed and reused independently, like a news article or blog post.

<section>:

Represents a generic section of content.
Often has a heading and groups related content together.

<aside>:

Represents content that is tangentially related to the content around it.
Often used for sidebars or additional information.

footer>:

Represents a footer section.
Typically contains metadata, copyright information, and links to related documents.

4>â€¢ Canvas and SVG tags 
=<canvas> Tag:
Purpose:
The <canvas> element is used for rendering bitmap graphics, allowing for dynamic, scriptable rendering of 2D shapes, images, and animations.
Drawing Model:
It provides a raster graphics API through JavaScript, where you can draw directly on the canvas pixel by pixel.
Usage:
Ideal for dynamic graphics and animations.

<svg> Tag:
Purpose:

The <svg> element is used for rendering scalable vector graphics (SVG), which are resolution-independent and can be scaled without loss of quality.
Drawing Model:

SVG uses XML-based markup to define vector shapes, paths, and text. Graphics in SVG are described mathematically.
Usage:

Ideal for static graphics, illustrations, and diagrams. It's suitable for scenarios where scalability and clarity are important.
